bug.short_desc: [build path] Add access rule to xml.jar from VM results in build that blocks UI

long_desc.thetext:
I got into a state where my workspace wouldn't build because PDE indicated that there was an access restriction on the packages in xml.jar of an IBM 1.4.2 VM. On the project Build Path property page, I added an access rule that gave access to all packages. This resulted in a busy cursor while the build took place. It would be better if the build occurred in the background.
P.S. I'm still trying to figure out why this jar all of a sudden had access rules associated with it. Any ideas?
JDT recently added this support.
See bug 163444. Build paths that reference execution environments are now subject to access rules. The rules reflect what packages exist at runtime.

Moving to JUI for comment. When the access rules for a jar in a JRE are modified, the JRE container initializer is asked to udpate the classpath immediately. I think the request should come after OK is pressed?
Note that access rules are supposed to be (will be) read-only on jars in an execution environment once JUI adds support (bug 166519).

The build path page directly applies changes to classpath container children attributes for the following reasons: - when telling the container to apply a change, it's up to the container to decide on how to update. It can reject certain changes, slightly modify a change or also update oder container children. Only by applying we can find out whats the result and the build path page would like to reflect the correct state. You can say that this is a shortcoming of the update protocol, and I agree. - classpath containers typically are also configurable on other preference/property pages: JRE install and user libraries. The direct apply solves the consistency problem.
In the future we will provide a possibility to the JRE container to not allow any changes to the access rules. I could implement some tricks so that the build is only done in the background (turn autobuild off, apply change, turn autobuild on, build in background).
Darin, what do you think?

Since the container has no idea of what context it has been called from, it cannot determine when/how to trigger the update (except immediately). Yes, I would suggest to use the auto-build on/off hack for now.
For M4 I set the accessrules attribute for JRE container children to read-only. Will look for a more general solution in M5.
bug 168077 describes the API that the UI needs to control witch attributes are read-only.
As mentioned, access rules modifications are now disabled. Currently hard coded, but in M7 we'll use the new API from bug 168077. I created bug 178006 for this. Marking this bug as fixed.
Verified in I20070321-0010

bug.short_desc: User is repeatedly prompted to load changes from the file system

long_desc.thetext:
Steps to reproduce:
1) Create a TPTP JUnit with a test method 2) Open both the test suite editor and the test class 3) Select the test class and change the comment for the method that was added. e.g. add "method description" as part of the comment. Save the test class. 3) Select the test suite editor. Notice that the user is prompted to load changes from the filesystem despite not making any changes to the test class or the editor from the filesystem. 4) Select the test class again and make any minor change (e.g. add a space). Save the test class. 5) Selecting the test suite editor will prompt the user with the same question.
This defect is pretty annoying

Jerome,
Any word on when this will be fixed? I find this extremely annoying when working with TPTP JUnit editors.

It seems that it is a more a TPTP junit test generation problem than a editor one. As soon as the java code is edited and saved, the test generation builder is called in order to refresh the test suite according to the new java file content.
If your change (such as comment modification) does not imply changes in the test suite model, the test suite editor should not be updated. What I suspect is that the builder is not smart enough to distinguish the cases where the test suite should be updated or not.
Julien, could you please, confirm/invalidate this analysis ?

I think there are two different issues here:
a) The model is kept in sync with the code, so if you make a code change that needs to be reflected in the model, then it is expected that the .testsuite gets modified. Starting with 4.3, javadoc comments are synchronized with model comments. So step 3) is an expected behavior: if you modify a test method javadoc comment, this comment will be copied into the associated test case description. However, behavior in 5) looks like a defect. If you just add a space to the file, it shouldn't impact the model. I don't reproduce this problem, maybe this is specific to your file, or to the modification you make. Ali, can you file a separate defect, and attach your .java and .testsuite files, and a description of the minor change you make to your code?
b) I agree that since the changes do not come from an external editor, the prompt should not appear (unless there are unsaved changes in the test suite editor). Jerome, I think you need to provide the builder with the infrastructure necessary to disable this prompt when changes come from an internal tool.

You don't need a specific type of JUnit class to be able to reproduce this defect. I can reproduce it using the steps that I've included. Can you make sure that you're following the steps exactly as outlined in the description?
Targeting to future since not containable in 4.4.

As discussed on this week's Test Project call (January 22, 2007), the Test Project will focus on existing P1 - P2/Blocker - Major and P1/Normal and test creation/automation defects (omitting defects dependant on outstanding features) in TPTP 4.4. All other Test Project defects have been targeted to future.

Bring up eclipse and check that everything comes up as desired using About Eclipse:Plugin-Details/Feature Details, Help:Manage Configuration, etc. 3. Exit eclipse. 4. Drop in a new set of features/plugins to the same site. 5. Bring up eclipse again and check that the correct set of plugins are installed. 6. Bring up Help:Manage Configuration and notice that the new features from step 4 are shown with errors on them because the plugins associated with them are not installed.

The rules for part_ref and procedure_designator are ambiguous and allow invalid code to be accepted for a call statement. For example, look at the following code:
call hello(i)(j,k,z)
end
This is currently accepted by the parser even though it is invalid. The problem is that in matching a data_ref for procedure_designator, the (..) is matched as part of the data_ref (actually, it's matched in part_ref, which is called by data_ref, to be more accurate). Then, upon returning to procedure_designator, the parser is still looking for an optional (..). This appears to be an ambiguity in the grammar that could be fixed by only allowing data_ref to match the (..) since procedure_designator only has one alternative, which is a data_ref.

Created an attachment (id=55076) shows invalid call statement that the parser accepts
This testcase illustrates a bug in call statements where the parser accepts invalid code.
Test case has been added to tests/bug-reports.

bug.short_desc: Pause on thread group disabled if any thread already suspended

long_desc.thetext:

Are you referring to thread groups or the JDIDebugTarget?
The JDI debug target does experience the behaviour that you describe. The suspend action can be changes to be enabled as long as at least one thread is running. The only problem with this behaviour is that threads that are not visible (such as filtered out system threads) would suddenly become visible when they are suspended.
Implementing suspend/resume on thread groups is more difficult. Currently there is no ability to suspend or resume a thread group, which makes me think you were referring to the debug target containing all threads.
